## WHAT IS NOW COVERED

- **`q == 1` pad collapse, SHAKE (`0x9F`)**: `shake128_cavp_len1336` (167 B = rate-1),
  `shake256_cavp_len1080` (135 B = rate-1), and again ACROSS a block boundary at
  `shake128_cavp_len2680` (335 B = 2*rate-1) and `shake256_cavp_len2168` (271 B).
- **`q == 1` pad collapse, SHA-3 (`0x86`)**: `sha3_256_cavp_len1080` (135 B at rate 136) and
  `sha3_512_cavp_len568` (71 B at rate 72).
- **`q == 2`, the minimal two-byte pad** (the neighbouring branch, so a mis-placed comparison is
  caught): `shake128_cavp_len1328`, `shake256_cavp_len1072`, `sha3_256_cavp_len1072`,
  `sha3_512_cavp_len560`.
- **`q == rate`, a message that is an exact multiple of the rate** and therefore needs a WHOLE extra
  pad block: `shake128_cavp_len1344`, `shake256_cavp_len1088`, `sha3_256_cavp_len1088`,
  `sha3_512_cavp_len576`.
- **Multi-block absorb** (2, 3 and 5 `keccakF` invocations in `absorb`): `shake128_cavp_len1352`,
  `shake128_cavp_len2688`, `shake128_cavp_long2696`, `shake128_cavp_long5400` (675 B),
  `shake256_cavp_len1096`, `shake256_cavp_len2176`, `shake256_cavp_long2184`,
  `shake256_cavp_long4376` (547 B), `sha3_256_cavp_long2184`, `sha3_512_cavp_long1160`.
- **Multi-block squeeze** (the inter-block `keccakF` in `squeeze`, which no DIRECT Keccak KAT touched,
  every one of them squeezing 32 or 64 bytes -- i.e. strictly under every rate):
  `shake256_cavp_var_c675` (137 B = rate+1, so it reads byte 0 of the second squeeze block) and
  `shake256_cavp_var_c1240` (250 B).
- **Squeeze truncation**: `shake256_cavp_var_c0` (2 bytes out of a 136-byte block),
  `shake256_cavp_var_c670` (exactly one full rate block), `shake128_cavp_var_c1116` (140 of 168).
- **Three distinct rates**: 168 (SHAKE128), 136 (SHAKE256 / SHA3-256), 72 (SHA3-512) -- rate 72 was
  previously exercised only by two short inputs, and never across a block boundary.
- **Both domain bytes**: `0x1F` (SHAKE) and `0x06` (SHA-3), each at its own `q == 1` collapse.

## WHAT IS STILL NOT COVERED (named, not hidden)

- **The FIPS 202 `forall` refinement remains OPEN.** There is no FIPS 202 specification in this tree,
  so there is no theorem of the form `forall msg, shake256 msg n = Fips202.SHAKE256 msg n`. Everything
  here is finitely many input/output pairs. A wrong implementation that happens to agree with the
  permutation on these 35 messages is not excluded by any argument in this file. Closing it needs, in
  order: (a) a Lean transcription of FIPS 202 sec. 3 (the five step mappings theta/rho/pi/chi/iota over
  the 5x5x64 state as a bit-addressed `Fin 5 -> Fin 5 -> Fin 64 -> Bool`) and sec. 6 (`SPONGE`,
  `pad10*1`), written against the standard rather than against this code; (b) a lane-indexing bridge
  lemma proving the `UInt64`-lane/little-endian representation here refines that bit-addressed state;
  (c) a round-function equality by `decide` over the bit indices; (d) an induction over blocks for
  `absorb` and over output blocks for `squeeze`. Steps (b) and (d) are the real work. This is the SAME
  class of residual as `NttFaithful` closed for the NTT, so the pattern exists in-tree.
- **Keccak-f itself is not independently pinned.** The permutation is only observed through the sponge.
  NIST publishes no CAVP vector for the bare permutation.
- **The CAVP Monte-Carlo files are not used** (`SHAKE128Monte.rsp`, `SHA3_512Monte.rsp`, and the rest).
  They chain thousands of iterations and would be a genuinely independent long-run check; not pinned.
- **SHA3-224 / SHA3-384 are not pinned** -- this tree defines neither.
- **SHAKE128 multi-block squeeze specifically is not pinned**: the CAVP `SHAKE128VariableOut.rsp` caps
  output at 1120 bits = 140 bytes, below the 168-byte rate. `squeeze` is rate-parametric and its
  multi-block path IS covered at rate 136, but not at rate 168.
- **The `"abc"` vectors in `Keccak.lean` / `MlKemDecaps.lean` have no NIST-file provenance.** They are
  reference-implementation cross-checks. They are no longer load-bearing: every branch they touch is
  now also covered by a digest-cited CAVP vector. See the citation notes added to those files.

## RESIDUAL (trusted base)

`native_decide`, i.e. `Lean.ofReduceBool` + `Lean.trustCompiler` -- the compiled-evaluation residual,
the same one the existing nine KATs and the ACVP pinning modules already carry. `native_decide` is
acceptable for a KAT: the win here is BRANCH COVERAGE and PROVENANCE, not a reduction in trusted base.
No `sorry`, no user `axiom`.

Non-vacuity was probed adversarially: single-nibble tampers of pinned vectors were checked to make the
corresponding equality evaluate to `false` (results recorded in the crypto TCB ledger).
-/
