/-! ## Branch-reachability witnesses.

The coverage claims in the header are MACHINE-CHECKED here rather than merely asserted. These
`#guard`s show (a) that the vectors above really do drive `pad` / `sha3Pad` into the `q == 1`
collapse and `absorb` into more than one block, and (b) that the pre-existing nine KATs on the empty
string and `"abc"` really did NOT. If someone later deletes the long vectors, these witnesses still
document which branch each message length selects. -/

-- The `q == 1` collapse IS reached at rate-1, and emits the merged byte (`0x9F` for SHAKE).
#guard (Keccak.pad 136 (List.replicate 135 0x00)).length == 136
#guard (Keccak.pad 136 (List.replicate 135 0x00)).getLast! == 0x9F
#guard (Keccak.pad 168 (List.replicate 167 0x00)).getLast! == 0x9F

-- ... and `0x86` for SHA-3, at both SHA-3 rates.
#guard (MlKemDecaps.sha3Pad 136 (List.replicate 135 0x00)).getLast! == 0x86
#guard (MlKemDecaps.sha3Pad 72 (List.replicate 71 0x00)).getLast! == 0x86
#guard (MlKemDecaps.sha3Pad 72 (List.replicate 71 0x00)).length == 72

-- The neighbouring `q == 2` branch emits TWO distinct bytes, not the merged one.
#guard (Keccak.pad 136 (List.replicate 134 0x00)).drop 134 == [0x1F, 0x80]
#guard (MlKemDecaps.sha3Pad 72 (List.replicate 70 0x00)).drop 70 == [0x06, 0x80]

-- THE OLD EVIDENCE, restated as a witness: the empty string and `"abc"` both pad to exactly ONE
-- block and both take the `else` branch, so neither could ever have caught a `q == 1` bug.
#guard (Keccak.pad 136 []).length == 136
#guard (Keccak.pad 136 [0x61, 0x62, 0x63]).length == 136
#guard (Keccak.pad 136 []).drop 134 == [0x00, 0x80]
#guard (MlKemDecaps.sha3Pad 72 []).length == 72

-- Multi-block absorb IS reached: an exact-rate message needs a whole extra pad block, and the long
-- vectors need three and five.
#guard (Keccak.pad 136 (List.replicate 136 0x00)).length == 272          -- 2 blocks
#guard (Keccak.pad 136 (List.replicate 273 0x00)).length == 408          -- 3 blocks
#guard (Keccak.pad 168 (List.replicate 675 0x00)).length == 840          -- 5 blocks
#guard (MlKemDecaps.sha3Pad 72 (List.replicate 145 0x00)).length == 216  -- 3 blocks at rate 72

-- Multi-block SQUEEZE is reached only by the VariableOut vectors: every pre-existing KAT squeezed
-- 32 or 64 bytes, i.e. strictly one block at every rate in this tree.
#guard (137 + 136 - 1) / 136 == 2   -- shake256_cavp_var_c675 -> 2 squeeze blocks
#guard (250 + 136 - 1) / 136 == 2   -- shake256_cavp_var_c1240 -> 2 squeeze blocks
